:"text","url":"/docs/tips/organization#organizing-your-server","content":"<File name=\"eup-clothing\" />"},"114":{"id":"/docs/tips/organization-40","page_id":"/docs/tips/organization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/organization#organizing-your-server","content":"<File name=\"custom_peds\" />"},"115":{"id":"/docs/tips/organization-41","page_id":"/docs/tips/organization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/organization#organizing-your-server","content":"<File name=\"mrpd\" />"},"116":{"id":"/docs/tips/organization-42","page_id":"/docs/tips/organization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/organization#organizing-your-server","content":"<File name=\"hospital\" />"},"117":{"id":"/docs/tips/organization-43","page_id":"/docs/tips/organization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/organization#organizing-your-server","content":"<File name=\"traffic_signs\" />"},"118":{"id":"/docs/tips/organization-44","page_id":"/docs/tips/organization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/organization#organizing-your-server","content":"<File name=\"weapon_pack\" />"},"119":{"id":"/docs/tips/organization-45","page_id":"/docs/tips/organization","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/organization#there-is-no-correct-way","content":"The exact folder names don't matter. What's important is that you choose a structure that makes sense to you and stay consistent. If every vehicle lives in one place, every map in another, and every script has a logical home, maintaining your server becomes significantly easier as it grows."},"120":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","type":"page","content":"Writing Maintainable Code","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Getting Started","Tips & Tricks"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/tips/writing-code"},"121":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-0","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#use-meaningful-names","content":"Use Meaningful Names"},"122":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-1","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#keep-functions-small","content":"Keep Functions Small"},"123":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-2","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#avoid-deep-nesting","content":"Avoid Deep Nesting"},"124":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-3","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#dont-repeat-yourself-dry","content":"Don't Repeat Yourself (DRY)"},"125":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-4","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#keep-globals-to-a-minimum","content":"Keep Globals to a Minimum"},"126":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-5","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#comment-the-why-not-the-what","content":"Comment the \"Why\", not the \"What\""},"127":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-6","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#be-consistent","content":"Be Consistent"},"128":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-7","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#remove-dead-code","content":"Remove Dead Code"},"129":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-8","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#dont-optimize-too-early","content":"Don't Optimize Too Early"},"130":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-9","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#leave-the-code-better-than-you-found-it","content":"Leave the Code Better Than You Found It"},"131":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-10","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#final-thoughts","content":"Final Thoughts"},"132":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-11","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code","content":"Writing code that *works* is only half the battle. Writing code that's easy to read, understand and modify months later is what separates a good developer from a great one. As your project grows, you'll find yourself spending far more time reading and maintaining existing code than writing new code. These practices make that experience much more enjoyable, for both yourself and anybody else that works on your project."},"133":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-12","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#use-meaningful-names","content":"Variable and function names should be easily descriptive for what purpose they serve, not saving a few keystrokes."},"134":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-13","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#use-meaningful-names","content":"Bad"},"135":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-14","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#use-meaningful-names","content":"Good"},"136":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-15","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#use-meaningful-names","content":"Someone reading your code shouldn't have to guess what `p` or `c` actually means."},"137":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-16","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#keep-functions-small","content":"A function generally should do one thing. Instead of creating one large function that handles multiple responsibilities like `SpawnVehicle()`, break it up into smaller functions like `LoadModel()`, `CreateVehicle()`, `SetupVehicle()`, `GetVehicleKeys()`. Smaller functions are easier to read, test, debug and can be reused instead of rewriting the same code a dozen times."},"138":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-17","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#avoid-deep-nesting","content":"Code that is nested several levels deep quickly becomes difficult to follow."},"139":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-18","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#avoid-deep-nesting","content":"Bad"},"140":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-19","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#avoid-deep-nesting","content":"Good"},"141":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-20","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#avoid-deep-nesting","content":"Using early returns reduces indentation and makes your intent much clearer."},"142":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-21","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#dont-repeat-yourself-dry","content":"If you find yourself copying and pasting code, ask yourself if it should be a function instead."},"143":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-22","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#dont-repeat-yourself-dry","content":"Bad"},"144":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-23","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#dont-repeat-yourself-dry","content":"Good"},"145":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-24","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#dont-repeat-yourself-dry","content":"If you need to change the logic later, you only need to change it in one place."},"146":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-25","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#keep-globals-to-a-minimum","content":"Keep the global scope as clean as possible, when you can always localize functions and variables."},"147":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-26","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#keep-globals-to-a-minimum","content":"Bad"},"148":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-27","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#keep-globals-to-a-minimum","content":"Good"},"149":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-28","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#comment-the-why-not-the-what","content":"Good comments will explain *why* something is happening, not *what* is happening. People reading your code should be able to understand *what* is happening just by reading it."},"150":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-29","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#comment-the-why-not-the-what","content":"Bad"},"151":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-30","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#comment-the-why-not-the-what","content":"Good"},"152":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-31","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#comment-the-why-not-the-what","content":"If the code clearly explains *what* it's doing, there's no need to repeat it. Additionally, you shouldn't just spam comments throughout your entire codebase, if it isn't obvious why something is done in a way that's when we'd recommend adding a comment to explain why."},"153":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-32","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#be-consistent","content":"Consistency is more important than personal preference. Choose a naming style and stick with it, for example:"},"154":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-33","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#be-consistent","content":"`playerPed`"},"155":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-34","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#be-consistent","content":"`playerCoords`"},"156":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-35","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#be-consistent","content":"`vehicleEntity`"},"157":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-36","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#be-consistent","content":"`spawnPosition`"},"158":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-37","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#be-consistent","content":"Don't mix multiple naming conventions throughout the same project. Consistency also applies to formatting. Whether you use tabs or spaces, `snake_case` or `camelCase`, choose one style and stick with it throughout your project. Consistent formatting makes code much easier to read."},"159":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-38","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#remove-dead-code","content":"Commented-out code quickly becomes clutter. If you're no longer using it, delete it. That's one of the reasons why we utilize version control like `Git`, you can always recover the old code if you need it. If you aren't using the code anymore, delete it."},"160":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-39","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#dont-optimize-too-early","content":"While this sounds counter productive, focus on writing readable and functioning code before micro optimizations. Write code that works, profile it, and *then* optimize the parts that actually need it."},"161":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-40","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#dont-optimize-too-early","content":"Premature optimization often makes code more difficult to understand without providing any meaningful performance improvements."},"162":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-41","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#leave-the-code-better-than-you-found-it","content":"Whenever you're working in a file, look for small improvements you can make. Maybe that's renaming a confusing variable, removing unused code, improving a comment or something else. Small improvements add up over time and make your project much easier to maintain."},"163":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-42","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#final-thoughts","content":"Maintainable code isn't about writing clever code, it's about writing code that's easy for someone else to understand. That \"someone else\" usually ends up being you, six months from now."},"164":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-43","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#final-thoughts","content":"Future you will thank present you for writing clean, organized and readable code. Here's some more resources for you to reference:"},"165":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-44","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#final-thoughts","content":"Effective FiveM Lua"},"166":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-45","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#final-thoughts","content":"Lua's Beginners Guide"},"167":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-46","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#final-thoughts","content":"Packt Lua QuickStart Guide"},"168":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-47","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#final-thoughts","content":"Lua Manual"},"169":{"id":"/docs/tips/writing-code-48","page_id":"/docs/tips/writing-code","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/tips/writing-code#final-thoughts","content":"Code is read far more often than it's written. Optimize for readability first."},"170":{"id":"/docs/free/bug-reports","page_id":"/docs/free/bug-reports","type":"page","content":"Simple Bug Reports","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Resources","Free","Simple Bug Reports"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/free/bug-reports"},"171":{"id":"/docs/free/changelog","page_id":"/docs/free/changelog","type":"page","content":"Simple Changelog System","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Resources","Free","Simple Changelog System"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/free/changelog"},"172":{"id":"/docs/free/chat","page_id":"/docs/free/chat","type":"page","content":"Simple Chat Toolbox","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Resources","Free","Simple Chat Toolbox"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/free/chat"},"173":{"id":"/docs/free/tackle","page_id":"/docs/free/tackle","type":"page","content":"Simple Tackle System","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Resources","Free","Simple Tackle System"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/free/tackle"},"174":{"id":"/docs/free/radio-animations","page_id":"/docs/free/radio-animations","type":"page","content":"Better Radio Anims","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Resources","Free","Better Radio Anims"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/free/radio-animations"},"175":{"id":"/docs/paid/airdrops","page_id":"/docs/paid/airdrops","type":"page","content":"Airdrops","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Resources","Paid","Airdrops"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/paid/airdrops"},"176":{"id":"/docs/paid/card-rooms","page_id":"/docs/paid/card-rooms","type":"page","content":"Card Rooms","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Resources","Paid","Card Rooms"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/paid/card-rooms"},"177":{"id":"/docs/paid/elevators","page_id":"/docs/paid/elevators","type":"page","content":"Simple Elevator System","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Resources","Paid","Simple Elevator System"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/paid/elevators"},"178":{"id":"/docs/paid/fire-signs","page_id":"/docs/paid/fire-signs","type":"page","content":"Fire Danger Signs","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Resources","Paid","Fire Danger Signs"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/paid/fire-signs"},"179":{"id":"/docs/paid/fuel","page_id":"/docs/paid/fuel","type":"page","content":"Advanced Fuel System","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Resources","Paid","Advanced Fuel System"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/paid/fuel"},"180":{"id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration","page_id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration","type":"page","content":"Configuration","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Resources","Paid","Garbage Job"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration"},"181":{"id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration-0","page_id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration#configuration--data-files","content":"Configuration & Data files"},"182":{"id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration-1","page_id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration#bridge--integration-configuration","content":"Bridge & Integration Configuration"},"183":{"id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration-2","page_id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration#locals--language","content":"Locals / Language"},"184":{"id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration-3","page_id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration#configuration--data-files","content":"All of the configuration & data files have detailed comments explaining how to configure everything to your liking, if you need assistance please reach out to us via Discord."},"185":{"id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration-4","page_id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration#configuration--data-files","content":"The main config file is located at `data/configuration.lua` and handles the general configuration data."},"186":{"id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration-5","page_id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration#configuration--data-files","content":"The locations data file is located at `data/locations.lua` and handles all of the location-specific information like ped locations, return points, etc"},"187":{"id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration-6","page_id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration#configuration--data-files","content":"The outfits data file is located at `data/outfits.lua` and handles all of the outfit information."},"188":{"id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration-7","page_id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration#configuration--data-files","content":"The props data file is located at `data/props.lua` and handles all of the prop information for dumpsters, bins & bags. This is also where you can adjust the amounts you get per trash type."},"189":{"id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration-8","page_id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration#configuration--data-files","content":"The zone names data file is located at `data/zone_names.lua` and is just a list of zone names, you most likely wont need to edit this."},"190":{"id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration-9","page_id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration#configuration--data-files","content":"The zones data file is located at `data/zones.lua` and includes over a dozen preconfigured zones around the map."},"191":{"id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration-10","page_id":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/paid/garbage-job/configuration#bridge--integration-configuration","content":"All of the framework and resource integrations can be found in the `bridge` directory, we expect you to have at least a basic understanding of Lua & how to integrate with other resources to edit these. Minimal support will be provided. If you have anything you want to recommend we integrate with, please l