g started on making a server or writing code, it's best that you choose an IDE/code editor that makes sense for what you are doing. In FiveM, the primary language you'll be interacting with is `lua`. `lua` is very beginner friendly and is easy to work with, that being said it's also supported in dozens of different code editors."],[55,"Before reaching out for support, take the time to:"],[174,"Better Radio Anims"],[182,"Bridge & Integration Configuration"],[294,"Bridge & Integration Configuration"],[269,"Bridge included with hooks to add your own integrations (ie, when trash is added to a truck, when a player is clocked in and out & more)"],[386,"Bridge system included with hooks for custom integrations and extensions."],[349,"Built from the ground up with scalability and compatibility in mind, the system supports multiple departments, realistic investigation tools, AI-assisted utilities, and configurable policing workflows - all structured to work seamlessly together or independently."],[176,"Card Rooms"],[19,"Choosing an IDE"],[18,"Choosing an IDE/Editor"],[380,"Clean framework abstraction"],[321,"Client"],[210,"clockIn"],[211,"clockOut"],[169,"Code is read far more often than it's written. Optimize for readability first."],[138,"Code that is nested several levels deep quickly becomes difficult to follow."],[16,"Codecademy Git Course"],[213,"collectPayment"],[37,"Color Highlight by Jason Lee"],[126,"Comment the \"Why\", not the \"What\""],[159,"Commented-out code quickly becomes clutter. If you're no longer using it, delete it. That's one of the reasons why we utilize version control like `Git`, you can always recover the old code if you need it. If you aren't using the code anymore, delete it."],[383,"Compatibility with existing server ecosystems"],[267,"Compatible with all major frameworks (QB, Qbox, ND, ESX) or works standalone."],[384,"Compatible with all major frameworks (QB, Qbox, ND, ESX) or works standalone."],[342,"Complete Police System"],[285,"Complete 